Caption: Fig. 1. Basic workflows common in supporting the enumerated tasks. In practice, many tasks are sequential or iterative as users see the nature of available data or find an answer that leads to more questions.

Fig. 2. The Find Subjects section. Controls at the top change the chart category and sorting. The ‘+’ control left of each bar is used to expand the category into bars for each specific vaccine product.

Fig. 3. The Active Filters area before and after filtering a selection. Any data selection appears as a filter preview in the box outlined in teal. The selection’s counts are in teal numbers before the current totals in black to preview the impact of filtering. After filtering, the selection collapses to a filter box that can be edited by clicking, removed with the X, or restored with an ‘undo’ link. These features allow the quick, non-destructive test of the influence a filter has on the current view.

Fig 4. Detail view of the Plot, showing antibody neutralization of HIV over time, where each of three studies has a row of events below. Event icons indicate vaccination, follow-up, and challenge (not pictured) events. The alignment has been changed such that zero is the time point of last vaccination. This clearly shows a cross-study pattern of an immune response curve peaking shortly after the last vaccination, which is obfuscated when aligning studies by their start day. Color and shape correspond to the combination of vaccine types received. Studies redacted.

Fig. 5. Plot comparing NAb response to four different HIV antigen clades. Color and shape co-vary and indicate the combination of vaccine classes administered. Color makes it clear that not all combinations were tested against all clades. Clades C and CRF01_AE are higher because subjects were vaccinated with parts of HIV from those clades. The undefined values did not report antigen clade.

Fig. 7. Correlation of two assays (NAb y, ELISpot x) across two different vaccine class combinations (color and shape). Separate sections for x values labelled “≤ 0” show points with undefined log values. They appear to the left of a gray stroke in both the correlation area above and the gutter below (a). The gutter plot with undefined values for y appears because ELISpot was tested additional times when NAb was not (b). The product class combination shown with green + symbols shows stronger ELISpot responses than the dark circles.

Fig. 6. The variable selector showing one of two recommended choices with broadest utility selected by default. The recommendations sit atop a longer list of available variables. On the bottom, a panel reveals the independent dimensions required to precisely define some variables. The dimensions default to suggested settings.
